> Just noticed this ([sharplab](https://sharplab.io/#v2:EYLgtghglgdgPgAQAwAIEEYAsBuAsAKAIQGY0AmFAYQIG8CUG1SMA2FASQBkoBnAFwA8sPgD4UAWQAUAShQBeMQG10AGhRk1ADjWYAunnwBfIA==)):
> 
> ```csharp
> public static IList<int> M() => [1, 2, 8, 4];
> ```
> ```csharp
> List<int> list = new List<int>();
> CollectionsMarshal.SetCount(list, 4);
> Span<int> span = CollectionsMarshal.AsSpan(list);
> int num = 0;
> span[num] = 1;
> num++;
> span[num] = 2;
> num++;
> span[num] = 8;
> num++;
> span[num] = 4;
> num++;
> return list;
> ```
> 
> It seems there's a fair amount of extra IL just to keep track of that index that's incremented every time, which also makes it not a constant (which might be less useful for the JIT). Is there any specific reason why Roslyn is doing this rather than just emitting:
> ```csharp
> List<int> list = new List<int>();
> CollectionsMarshal.SetCount(list, 4);
> Span<int> span = CollectionsMarshal.AsSpan(list);
> span[0] = 1;
> span[1] = 2;
> span[2] = 8;
> span[3] = 4;
> return list;
> ```
> The latter might even allow the JIT to vectorize some of these assignments, in theory (also the IL seems smaller too?).

## Background and Motivation

In our Application we have a class that implements `IEnumerable<T>` and has a `Add(T)` method. However this is unnecessary for the user to know. 99% of the time the other 99% of the methods are used. Thus it seems counter intuitive to use `[]` instead of  `new()`. Even though the emitted code might be the same code, it conveys a different meaning. Our class is not "just a collection".

currently we have a pattern/design like this (simplified):
```cs
internal class MyClass
{
  public void Do()
  {
    using Context ctx = new();
//                      ^- IDE0028: Collection initialization can be simplified
    SomeEntity thing = ctx.Get(123);
    SomeEntity other = ctx.CreateNew();
    ctx.Commit();
  }
}

public sealed class Context : IEnumerable<SomeEntity>, IDisposable
{
  public void Add(SomeEntity entity) { }
  public SomeEntity Get(int key) => new();
  public SomeEntity CreateNew() => new();
  public void Commit() { }
  public IEnumerator<SomeEntity> GetEnumerator() => throw new NotImplementedException();
  IEnumerator IEnumerable.GetEnumerator() => throw new NotImplementedException();
  public void Dispose() => throw new NotImplementedException();
}

public sealed class SomeEntity
{ 
...
}
```

## Proposed API

Since changing the implementation is out of the question due to far too many usages and possible breaking changes, it would be great to have something akin to this, from where the analyzers would infer to not pursue any optimization/analysis for this type.
```diff
+[NoCollectionInitializer]
public sealed class Context : IEnumerable<SomeEntity>, IDisposable
{
...
}
```

Further extending on that, there might be a Parameter on the attribute that could change the agressiveness. For Example:
`NoCollectionInitializer(Aggressive=false)` (default?) would only stop the analyzers from generating suggestions. `NoCollectionInitializer(Aggressive=true)` could make the compiler emit a warning or error, because collection initialization is strictly not allowed.

## Usage Examples
the function `MyClass.Do()`would not contain any Diagnostics after applying the Attribut to `Context`

